{"id": "2953350", "revid": "112744", "url": "https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=2953350", "title": "Air pollution in California found to increase COVID-19 risk", "text": " \nA study published August 2 cites air pollution in the in California as a factor for increased infection and death due to COVID-19 in the state, media recently reported.\nThe first study to assess air pollution and COVID-19, researchers with the Public Health Institute and linked neighborhoods with high levels of particulate matter in air samples with a higher susceptibility to coronavirus infection and death. The microscopic particles can penetrate deep into the lungs of residents, making them more vulnerable to respiratory and cardiovascular disease. Results from the study showed residents in counties with higher levels of particulate matter: , , and , and parts of , Orange, and , had a 20% higher risk of infection and a 51% higher risk of death due to COVID-19. \nIn all, 8.5% of all deaths, or approximately 4,250, were found to be potentially avoidable if the state had uniformly low air pollution. Those examined were 3.1 million COVID-19 infections and nearly 50,000 deaths in the state of California between February 2020 and February 2021, \nDr. Paul English with the Public Health Institute and the lead author of the study noted low income and Hispanic communities were found to be disproportionately affected: \"People of color live in communities that have some of the worst air pollution and also have greater chances of getting sick and even greater chances of dying from COVID. \n\"This is really concerning, especially in regions like the where wildfires are occurring right now and contributing to greater air pollution. We can save lives by making sure families and schools have access to free and low-cost air cleaners, and that outdoor workers receive paid time off and adequate personal protection during high-pollution events like wildfires\".\nThe San Joaquin Valley is prone to this pollution issue due to the region being surrounded by mountains which traps pollution from agriculture, automobiles traffic, and wildfires. Jamie Holt from the Valley Air District noted that \"Particulate matter is one of the issues we face here in the San Joaquin Valley. We are a valley, we're surrounded all sides by mountains, there's a climate that creates an inversion layer, which basically traps pollution.\"\nThis study was funded by the with technical assistance provided by the . "}
